A node is typed by attaching a type-label (a sort/class identifier) drawn from the graph's schema ontology, so that the node is treated as an instance of that class. Formally, given a knowledge graph G = (N, E, τ) with a typing function τ : N → T over a type hierarchy (T, ≤), typing node n means asserting τ(n) = t for some t ∈ T. Downstream queries and reasoners then use τ(n) to dispatch class-specific properties, constraints, and inference rules. Subtype polymorphism is supported via the partial order ≤ on T: if t ≤ t', then n also satisfies the obligations of t'. In RDF/OWL this is encoded as the triple ⟨n, rdf:type, t⟩, with t typically an owl:Class. In property graphs the same idea appears as a node label, e.g. Neo4j's `:Person` tag. Multi-typing is allowed when τ is relational rather than functional, letting one node belong to several classes simultaneously. Validation tools (SHACL, ShEx, schema constraints) then check that n's outgoing edges conform to the shape declared for type t.
